Title: Long Run - Knee safe
WorkoutDescription: Long run if your knee is not aggravated at all. Lets stay in touch this week to make sure we go into this confident that your knee isn't going to be pesky.
AthleteComments: *06/12/2025 Peter Oehlinger: Used this run to get a reference for future runs. This route is perfect for simulating Val dâ€™Aran. First two laps are on a shorter route but from lap 3 onwards one lap is 5.5km +315m vert which matches Val dâ€™Aran perfectly. The goal would be to stay below 30min and be able to hold this pace for 20 laps. Still a long way to go but itâ€™s always good to have a goal ðŸ˜Š @Anna: we should probably talk about how I should run the long runs. This time I pushed on the first four laps so that my HR on the ascents was always close to 158bpm (I crossed it for just one second on the last push lapâ€¦). This feels quite hard and I needed to back off after the fourth lap. Fueling: 98g/hour + less the a liter of water. I am not thirsty when itâ€™s cold. Knees: Yesterday I didnâ€™t feel anything on both knees. This morning, however, the left knee acted up a bit. Interestingly, when I started to run the right knee acted up a bit and the left knee felt silent. Super strange. But both times it was only minor pain (max pain 2 out of 10). After 5 min of running both knees felt good. They were not acting up again during the run. On the first two laps I felt amazing. Then, when my muscles started to get tired, I was a bit uncomfortable because I thought the knee pain might come back but they felt good throughout the entire run. Letâ€™s see how they feel in a couple of hours/tomorrow.* *06/12/2025 Anna DeMonte: Hey Peter! Great feedback and here are my recommendations: These long runs need to be mostly easy, with HR well below the ceiling so we donâ€™t accumulate fatigue that worsens knee symptoms or compromises quality later in the block. I know you like to push things, but this weekend run in this block is not meant to be up tempo (close to Lt1). We will add in more intense, closer to LT1 efforts later in the block, but now is the time for these to be long, easy, and build your aerobic capacity.* *06/12/2025 Anna DeMonte: That Lt1 heart rate is not a goal, its an "absolute ceiling" or moreso a hard "do not cross" line. In terms of Val d'Aran, this is great that we're starting to think about it, but far far too early to start looking at the paces. Another way to think of this is, your two strength sessions are very important. If you're feeling fatigued going into the next lift, we know we've gone too hard in the long run.* *06/12/2025 Anna DeMonte: Your fueling is excellent. No adjustments needed now* *06/12/2025 Anna DeMonte: Lastly, as far as we are concerned, this run is great information for the knee. It's encouraging that your pain isn't increasing, but also reiterates why we really want to keep these nice and easy!*

Title: Run (w/ Strides)
WorkoutDescription: Returning to run with strides in preparation for coming blocks We're going to be doing strides a couple times per week. To be done immediately after the run. These are not sprints. Overall Scheme 6 reps 20 seconds 1-2 minutes easy recovery in between https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SuSA9t0wM1Y Important Points Ease into these. Spend the first five seconds slowly come up onto pace. Run tall through the hips, with a slight forward lean Use long-distance form, with normal arm carriage and a relaxed upper body. No excessive arm drive like you would have running a 100m race. Stride should be like you are running a mile-5K. Instead of increasing cadence as high as you can go, emphasize knee drive and output-per-stride at a smooth effort. Let me know if you have any questions

Title: Peter: 160bpm 10% Incline Treadmill - HR Drift Test
WorkoutDescription: 30 DEC 25 // 158 test // .06% drift // 10% incline @ 9.3km pace *The only way this test works is by not changing the treadmill speed once you have started your 1h5m, just start the test, get in the zone, and finish the whole 65 minutes at that speed* Heat is a massive issue during these tests, you must have a fan on you during this to stay as cool as possible (unless the room is super cold). TEST 0-10 minutes: 135-150 BPM 10-15 minutes: 151-162BPM 15-19 minutes: 162-166 BPM (push up above 162 slightly so we can get it to stabilize lower) 19-22: bring HR back down to 160. This is our stabilization period. You can start the timer once we get at least one min of stable 162bpm. 22-86 minutes: actual test period. don't change speed, let your HR move/drift. Once your HR stabilizes at 160bpm, DO NOT change the speed at ALL the entire test. We are tracking here how your HR drifts up, not how your speed changes. This is different than the track test. Full directions below. I want you to do this at 15% on the treadmill and target 160 BPM. Warmup, get your HR to stabilize at 160, and then start the test. Once your HR hits 160bpm the metabolic processes have more or less started, so I recommend warming up for the first 10 minutes under 150 BPM. IMPORTANT -Treadmills sometimes have time limits (like 60min) make sure you set the treadmill to something like 90 minutes or more -If treadmill only goes up to 60, I recommend restarting the workout on the treadmill after the warmup so it doesn't shut off in the test -Try and minimize the interruption so your test starts right at 160 BPM (or as close as possible). Let me know if you have any questions. Make sure not to adjust the speed or incline of the treadmill once the 60 minutes has started We want your HR to be stable at 160, so ideally look for values around 160 for a minute or two before you start the test. Once stabilized, run for 1:05 (hour and five min) at the exact same speed.
AthleteComments: *30/12/2025 Peter Oehlinger: Treadmill AeT Test Incline: 10% Speed: 9.3km/h - 6:27min/km - 10:23min/mile Fueling: 45g before the run + 25g during warm up + 81g after the run Heat: no big issue. The combination of the treadmill fan and ice worked well. Thoughts: warm up was imo perfect. However, after pushing above 160, HR didnâ€™t settle back to 160 within 3 min. I lowered the pace quite a bit (from 10.5km/h to 9km/h). HR dropped as I reduced the pace too much. I increased it to 9.3km/h for the test but should have increased it a bit more. Just didnâ€™t want to adjust it 5min into the test and didnâ€™t want to fail (i.e. reduce the pace again).* *30/12/2025 Peter Oehlinger: Add: my left calf is so sore and I donâ€™t really understand why. It was already bad yesterday but today itâ€™s even worse. The only explanation I have is that I removed the tape on Sunday.* *30/12/2025 Anna DeMonte: 30 DEC 25 // 158 test // .06% drift // 10% incline @ 9.3km pace* *30/12/2025 Anna DeMonte: The calve soreness, did this come during the test? Actually, when we do these incline tests running, one of the first muscles to fatigue the most is calves as we raise the incline. I'd expect much of this soreness came from the test today* *30/12/2025 Peter Oehlinger: No it was already there. I had issues on Monday and today before the test it was really bad. The test didnâ€™t make it much worse though. Interestingly the test didnâ€™t fatigue the muscles too much. My right leg feels pretty good. But letâ€™s wait for tomorrow.*

Title: Peter: Run Power Work (No Sled)
WorkoutDescription: This isn't a conditioning workout, this is a power workout. Make sure you are completely rested between sets and not carrying much fatigue from exercise to exercise. Really focus on power output with each exercise. Eventually your power will start to fall off, pay attention to when this happens. After this point, the workout is of little effectiveness. Let me know how this sessions feels + how long it takes. Warmup 1) 10 min easy jog or bike 2) Dynamic drills: high knees, A-skips, bounding, hip openers 3) 2Ã—30 m accelerations (gradually building speed) 4) 2Ã—20 m skips for height + distance Plyometric Series 3 rounds total full recovery between rounds (2-3 min) 1) Single-Leg Hops (in place) 6-8/leg 2) Broad Jump 3Ã—2 jumps 3) Bounding (alternating legs) 2Ã—20 m https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b3124L0KK3Q 4) Lateral Skater Jumps 2Ã—6/side Strength-Speed Block Rest 2â€“3 min between sets 1) Single-Leg KB Swings 4Ã—6/leg Lightâ€“moderate (16â€“24 kg) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kGB1SwDHo3o 2) Explosive RDLs 4x4 (slow eccentric to mid shin, explosive concentric) 3) Trap Bar Deadlift Jumps 4x4 (Soft landing, 15-25% 1RM) 4) Vertical jump + stick 4 Ã— 3 - Max vertical jump, soft landing, hold position 2â€“3 seconds -Do not chase fatigue or extra height with poor mechanics https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gObPFKgofYE 5) Heavy kettlebell swings 3 Ã— 6 Heavy but still fast, powerful hip extension If speed drops, stop the set https://www.youtube.com/shorts/2gXtvqLa_T8

My jump height is a bit embarrassing ðŸ™ˆ but I love to work on it ðŸ˜Š At the end of the easy run following this workout I started to feel my legs. Plyometric Series Bounding is probably the most intense exercise in this series. In general no big issues. Feel the knee and ankle a bit but not pain. Strength-Speed Block 1) Single-Leg KB Swings 16kg with dumbbell. This is the most difficult exercise for me. I donâ€™t really know what I should focus on. 2) Explosive RDLs 60kg 3) Trap Bar Deadlift Jumps 30kg 4) Vertical jump + stick Need to start on my toes. This feels so much better 5) Heavy kettlebell swings 20kg last set 24kg with dumbbell* *01/01/2026 Anna DeMonte: This is really good feedback, thank you for writing it out. On the explosiveness and jump height, i'd say this is definitely not to be embarrassed about! This is exactly why we are doing this.  Power is a trainable quality, especially as we haven't emphasized it yet. The goal for these early sessions is how cleanly and explosively you move.* *01/01/2026 Anna DeMonte: Feedback on your legs toward the end of the easy run afterward is also expected. Title: Run (w/ Strides)
WorkoutDescription: Returning to run with strides in preparation for coming blocks We're going to be doing strides a couple times per week. To be done immediately after the run. These are not sprints. Overall Scheme 6 reps 20 seconds 1-2 minutes easy recovery in between https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SuSA9t0wM1Y Important Points Ease into these. Spend the first five seconds slowly come up onto pace. Run tall through the hips, with a slight forward lean Use long-distance form, with normal arm carriage and a relaxed upper body. No excessive arm drive like you would have running a 100m race. Stride should be like you are running a mile-5K. Instead of increasing cadence as high as you can go, emphasize knee drive and output-per-stride at a smooth effort. Let me know if you have any questions

Title: Peter: 15% Short Interval Workout 1
WorkoutDescription: 15% incline Very important you keep track of your paces and let me know in the comments. Ideally, always use the same machine for these speed sessions, treadmills are often out of calibration but using the same machine will at least keep the workout consistent. Warmup: 15 minutes Z1-Z2 4x20 second hard pushes with a 40 second rest in between 2 minutes at goal pace for the workout 2 minutes easy Working: 6x6 minutes. A good guide for the level of intensity here is possible on shitty day, comfortable-hard on a day when you are feeling strong. You should finish this workout and feel like you could do one or two more reps at the pace of your final rep. This is just a workout, just a stimulus like any other session. You should not look at these workouts as an assessment of your fitness. 1 minute rest. Your call how you use this time, but make it easy. 30 minutes cool down
AthleteComments: *22/01/2026 Peter Oehlinger: Workout felt good. It was hard but I could probably go a bit faster but it was a good start. Shin pain in the beginning but it was improving over time (this is a really good thing cause itâ€™s less likely to be a stress fracture). For the next days I will stick to the treadmill with around 10% incline. Title: Run (w/ Strides)
WorkoutDescription: Returning to run with strides in preparation for coming blocks We're going to be doing strides a couple times per week. To be done immediately after the run. These are not sprints. Overall Scheme 6 reps 20 seconds 1-2 minutes easy recovery in between https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SuSA9t0wM1Y Important Points Ease into these. Spend the first five seconds slowly come up onto pace. Run tall through the hips, with a slight forward lean Use long-distance form, with normal arm carriage and a relaxed upper body. No excessive arm drive like you would have running a 100m race. Stride should be like you are running a mile-5K. Instead of increasing cadence as high as you can go, emphasize knee drive and output-per-stride at a smooth effort. Let me know if you have any questions
